Hello Voyagers! :StarkNet: 

Together with **StarkNet Alpha mainnet release** next week we will be delivering enhanced version of **StarkNet Block Explorer - Voyager**!
Here is what you can expect from this release:

**Features**
* Contact verification

Voyager Team.

Author: perama
Content:
Hey 🙂

When using a `read` command, and the result contains a mixed combination of felts and arrays, I am seeing the explorer only return single values, rather than arrays:

https://goerli.voyager.online/contract/0x033668cdcf20672e4ce91652162888953474dee21c13ca9bdbea658f4b8f9059#readContract

Author: perama
Content:
In the linked contract, the `get_arbitrary_state_arrays` function , when passed the arguments:
```
1, 2, 3 
3
1, 2, 3 
3
```
The result should have some arrays: e.g., the third return value should be an array. In the CLI the results are returned appropriately, so I imagine it is a parsing issue in Voyager. Perhaps it is to do with long arrays (e.g., 96).

Author: bartleg
Content: Hi @perama we are looking into this. Thanks for the highlight!

Author: kasiagankiewicz#8410
Content: Hi @perama  Could you please share with us how would you like the data to be presented in Voyager? The same as it is in CLI? Could you please share a screenshot? That would be very helpful! Thank you!  🙏

Author: perama
Content:
I don't have a preference for how the arrays are returned (e.g., comma separated, space separated). 

This particular function returns variable length arrays, so the return values have the standard naming scheme: `array_name_len` preceding the `array_name`. I imagine that the most user friendly approach would be to have Voyager backend digest the length of the array, but not display it to the user.

For example, the CLI might return an array with length 5: `5 20 21 22 23 24`. The user probably only wants to see `20 21 22 23 24`

Here is the specific function for the contract I linked previously:

https://github.com/perama-v/GoL2/blob/main/contracts/GoL2_infinite.cairo#L606

Author: kasiagankiewicz#8410
Content: Thank you for sharing, we captured this and we will work on improving the response as an array!

Author: perama
Content: Thank you 🙂

Author: bartleg
Content:
Hello Voyagers!

We have some news to share. Following recent v.0.6.2 (https://discord.com/channels/793094838509764618/793094838509764621/919892930234286150) announcement we can share that a **new version of Voyager is available on Goerli**
🔗  https://goerli.voyager.online/
It will be also soon available on Mainnet.

**Improvements**

✅ **Pending block**: Mainnet blocks are closed at a 2h rate, this means that once a new pending block is seen on Voyager, it will take at least 2h until something new can be displayed again. With this advancement, Voyager can present also transactions from a block being built.
✅ **Hexadecimal values supported in the read and write contract calls**: The user can now provide input data to the read and write contract functions in two forms: decimal and hexadecimal (0x prefix). It is available for simple numeric fields. Implementation in array arguments will follow.
✅ **Minor UI improvements**

**Issues fixed**

✅ Redirection to prod even for the transaction madeon Goerli (contract function)
✅ Double contract source code displayed
✅ Wrong message hash calculating

Looking forward to your feedback!
Voyager Team

Author: bartleg
Content:
Hello Voyagers :StarkNet: 

New Voyager Block Explorer (v0.6.2) is already on **Mainnet**!

**Fixed bugs**
    
🐦Redirection to prod even the ttransacgtion was on Goerli (contract function)
🐦Double contract source code displayed
🐞Wrong message hash calculating
🐞Duplicate transaction/message bug 
🐞Invalid redirection in tabs after right click
 
**Improvements**
    
⭐ **Last pending block**: Mainnet blocks are closed at a 2h rate, this means that once a new pending block is seen on Voyager, it will take at least 2h until something new can be displayed again. With this advancement, Voyager can present also transactions from a block being built.
    
 🚀 **Hexadecimal values supported in the read and write contract calls**: The user can now provide input data to the read and write contract functions in two forms: decimal and hexadecimal (0x prefix). It is available for simple numeric fields. Implementation in array arguments will follow. 
    
⭐ **Enable searching in Verify Contract address field**: implemented a contract searching capability in the "Contract" address field on the "Verify contract" page.
    
⭐ **Add search by Message Hash to the search bar:** The user can now search by message hash from Voyager's search bar.
    
⭐ **Messages in Block details:** "Block details" page has new tab showing all messages correlated with this block
    
🚀  **Presenting arrays returned from write contract function calls**
    
🚀  **When presenting search results the first result is highlighted:** This allows for selecting with a single enter press when there is an exact match (i.e. when pasting a complete hash) 

We are looking forward to your feedback.
Voyager Team

Author: xjonathanlei
Content:
Bug report: I tried to query `balanceOf` on the TST token contract using a hex format address, gets zeros for both `low` and `high` when the actual balance is non-zero.

After inspecting the network requests made, **__it turns out when using hex format, there's an error converting the hex format into decimal__**: all digits after the first 16 are zero, as shown in the attached screenshot.

Steps to reproduce:
1. go to https://goerli.voyager.online/contract/0x07394cbe418daa16e42b87ba67372d4ab4a5df0b05c6e554d158458ce245bc10#readContract
2. call `balanceOf` with `0x01e4936b6feef2ac14bae6d93c9fc4feeac5120b45e4f5418218765814531c47`

Expected:
balance is non-zero, as calling with `856171432567971469060495778422850031844869372766225325283395369927552736327` (the decimal equivalent) returns non-zero

Actual:
both `low` and `high` are zero

Author: bartleg
Content:
Hello Voyagers :StarkNet: 

New Voyager Block Explorer (v0.7) is already on **Goerli**!

**Improvements**

⭐ **ArgentX** wallet integration
⭐ **Hex/decimal switch**: integrated a switch button that allows the users to choose if the response in contract function should be in hexadecimal or decimal format.
⭐ **L1 L2 Messages Tab**: improved and unified the view inside Messages tab (in transaction details), both L2 L1 and L1 L2.
⭐ **Support for struct arrays:** implemented an external function that receives/returns a struct array and allows the contract to be compiled. What it means from Voyager is to support the ability to input/output struct arrays in the read/write pages.
⭐ **UI:** minor improvements

**Fixed bugs**

🐞 Duplicated messages with wrong internal information
🐞 UI bug with long contract address: fixed a UI bug that was displaying too many zeros for deployed contracts.
🐞 Error 400 when validating contract: fixed a bug that was giving “400 error - The code does not match" when trying to verify contract on Goerli.
🐞 Fixed parsing of hexadecimal numbers in contract functions

We are looking forward to your feedback.
Voyager Team

Author: kasiagankiewicz#8410
Content:
Hello everyone! 👋 

Last Friday we had a release of a new version of Voyager which included the following features:

✅ Read functions with ArgentX - so far it was only possible to use write functions with ArgentX. Now we have extended this functionality and made it possible to use the read functions in the same way.
✅  When parsing transaction data according to the ArgentX convention:
    - Function name visible.
    - Possibility to convert each parameter separately.
✅  Supporting contract verification with multiple source files - now it is possible to verify the contract by importing multiple source files.
✅  Added redirection from not verified contracts to verification page.
✅  Added an information on read/write functions when the contract is not verified.
✅  Added error reason on rejected transactions.

The changes are available on both goerli and mainnet.
We appreciate any feedback on your experience with Voyager!
Voyager Team. 🚀 

Mainnet: https://voyager.online/
Goerli: https://goerli.voyager.online/

Author: kasiagankiewicz#8410
Content:
What functions did you call? Was there one input on the UI side? Or maybe there were two (low and high)?
The fact that calldata has two values ​​is a good thing. That Uint256  is that one input is displayed on the UI side (the user provides one value), then Voyager formats the data correctly and passes it further to the API (then already two values). 

So long story short: you should see one input on UI (no split on low and high) but two values ​​are sent to the API.

Author: guiltygyoza
Content:
Bug: strange behavior of calldata ordering

with both voyager and plain starknet.js, given the following hypothetical function signature:
```
func (arr_len : felt, arr : felt*, x : felt, y : felt):
...
```
voyager would show the right ordering in input boxes, but upon clicking "Transact", the calldata would show the incorrect order where `arr_len` and `arr` are sunk to the bottom of input args. This then (quite understandably) leads to tx not being able to be sent, with a vague `TRANSACTION_FAILED` message.

Author: guiltygyoza
Content: tagging @cecco_ - I originally found this bug while using starknet-react, then realized voyager exhibited the same behavior of incorrect calldata ordering. this could mean that the bug is with starknet.js

Author: kasiagankiewicz#8410
Content:
1. failed/rejected transactions are not visible in Voyager. Yet 🙂 currently Voyager displays only the transactions `ACCEPTED_ONCHAIN`, and on the basis of L1 the state update hash determines whether it is a transaction accepted on L1 or L2.
2. possible transaction statuses are: 
- `NOT_RECEIVED` - The transaction has not been received yet.
- `RECEIVED` - The transaction was received by the operator.
- `PENDING` - The transaction passed the validation and is waiting to be sent on-chain.
- `REJECTED` - The transaction failed validation and thus was skipped.
- `ACCEPTED_ONCHAIN` - The transaction was accepted on-chain.

Content: @kasiagankiewiczHey ser, may i ask what're 'address[1]' and 'selector[1]'? Thank you!

Author: kasiagankiewicz#8410
Content: address is the address of the contract that contains the called method, and selector is the selector of the called method. The indexes next to it are there to distinguish between methods because sometimes the calldata of a transaction can contain many called methods. 🙂

Author: gregoryguillou
Content: As you can see the amount type is uint256 which as a wider range than a Felt. uint256 is actually a struct with 2 members {low Felt, high Felt}; as a result the 0 is actually what is inside the high value of the uint256, i.e. in your case 0

Author: kasiagankiewicz#8410
Content:
Hi @BRRoy, coming with the answers 🙏 :
*I can’t find the link for checking my Token balances.*
Token balance is a feature that will be introduced in Voyager soon.

*I can’t see my incoming transactions. I funded my wallet with Layerswap but I don’t see the tx in my transaction history.*
At the moment, Voyager offers only deploy and invoke (interactions with the contract) transactions. We also have captured to add other (deposits) transactions in the future.

*Accounts deployed with Braavos or ArgentX (Verified and Live wallet providers) are tagged as “Not Verified”. (Not a big issue)*
Could you provide some examples of addresses? We will investigate this.

*I see the tx fee but not the amount transacted.*
Also we have a plan to display more information in transaction details.

*Transaction Types are mainly “INVOKE”. More tags will be helpful (deposit, approve, withdraw…)*
As above, at the moment in Voyager, we have developed two types of transactions:
- deploy - transaction related to deploying the contract
- invoke - a transaction related to the interaction of the contract,
we are planning deposit transactions soon. 
As for the names (deploy, invoke), they are the original names of the transaction types that come from StarkNet.

if you have any other suggestions, please feel free to share with us 😊 and thank you for your time 🙏

Author: kasiagankiewicz#8410
Content:
Hey, we currently have two status values in Voyager:
`verified` and `not verified`. Default value is `not verified`. In order for the contract to change its status from `not verified` to `verified`, it should be verified here (mainnet) https://voyager.online/verify or here (goerli) https://goerli.voyager.online/verifyby by entering the source code of given contract.

Author: svetylko.
Content: On https://starkstation.voyager.online/, there is "block verification cost". What is this precisely? Cost of compute of block verification? (Fee-storage cost for persisting it onto L1?)

Author: closer2282
Content:
This's related to components of StarkNet 
A Verifier is a smart contract on Ethereum that receives the newly generated proofs from the Prover as L1 transactions and validates them on-chain. The result of the validation is sent to the StarkNet’s Core smart contract for record keeping and to trigger a new set of L1 transactions from StarkNet to update the global state on-chain for record keeping.
So the cost includes gas fee charged by proofs validated on Ethereum, for details you can check this article
https://david-barreto.com/starknets-architecture-review/

Author: syedhaiderabbas
Content: Its the Total txn fees paid to verify a particular l2 block on Mainnet by StarkNet Operator

Author: svetylko.

Then the cost of running starknet will go from 0.029 ETH per block (total block fee) to 0.005 ETH (block verification cost) per block?

Author: milan3774
Content: gm chads, Voyager is not correctly converting u256 return value in a deployed Cairo 1 contract - e.g. in here https://goerli.voyager.online/contract/0x059a4016a63ea2efb46c94a18b87488cf5fd18925f9fa96af9d236d6c56a6b85#readContract the `a_u256` returns a 2^256-1 value, but Voyager only shows 2^128-1 (the `low` part)

Author: 0xbado
Content: Thanks for reporting @milan, we'll fix it!

Author: mempoolsurfer
Content:
There are only three types in Cairo 0: felt and felt* and structs. A 'uint256' is a struct of two felts (high and low) which are 128 bits each. So to give a uint256 you'd need to give two values as inputs. felt* is a raw type in cairo and points to a memory location. In call data (as part of a transaction for example) you need to give the length first and then all of the values.

Note none of this is very relevant in Cairo 1.0.

Author: ors3051
Content:
hey anon, we added Account calls! 🔥

Now with views on
🔗 account calls page 
🔗 a separate tab on contract page
🔗 account call details 

Take a deeper dive into the core of user activity on Starknet👇 
https://voyager.online/account-calls

Why Account Calls? 🧐
On ETH L1, with an EOA (Externally Owned Accounts), transactions directly call contracts, there’s no intermediaries.

On Starknet, you’re not sending a transaction directly to the contract that you want to call. Instead, you call the execute function of your Account Contract, meaning you’re sending the transaction to your own Account Contract, so it doesn’t show up in the TX page of the contract called. 

More info https://twitter.com/0xvoyageronline/status/1671131635339739136?s=20

The Account Calls table shows these interactions between Account Contract and the contract called.

👉 https://voyager.online/account-calls

Author: th0rgal.
Content:
Hello there,

I am trying to call a cairo 2 contract from voyager but I keep getting:
``Execution was reverted; failure reason: 0x4661696c656420746f20646573657269616c697a6520706172616d202331.
``

Where the failure reason translates to "Failed to deserialize param #1".

The function interface I am trying to call is:
```rs
fn standard_multicall(self: @TContractState, calls: Array<Call>) -> Array<Span<felt252>>;
```
And the Call interface is the following:
```rs
#[derive(Drop, Serde)]
struct Call {
    to: ContractAddress,
    selector: felt252,
    calldata: Array<felt252>
}
```

The only value it seems to work with is an empty array (calldata 0). When I try to get the result of an actual call like ``totalSupply()`` of the ``ether`` erc20 contract, it doesn't work.

Here is what I tried:
```1, 0x049d36570d4e46f48e99674bd3fcc84644ddd6b96f7c741b1562b82f9e004dc7, 0x80aa9fdbfaf9615e4afc7f5f722e265daca5ccc655360fa5ccacf9c267936d, 0
```
Which means:
```
calls_array_length, eth_contract_address, totalSupply_function_selector, calldata_len```

Author: th0rgal.
Content: The contract can be found here: https://goerli.voyager.online/contract/0x06a45c238f6485678dd0373b75a42085d8157573af3f78dcdad4e853eeaae9e9#readContract

Author: prix0007
Content: I Checked with  a sample contract with just taking the struct in params to check. And looks like the parameters are getting passed as expected to the contract. Can you share your contract also so I can debug and help further. Looks like it's more of a contract issue we are seeing here.

https://github.com/starknet-id/multicalls/blob/master/src/view.cairo#L32

Author: prix0007
Content:
Hey There @th0rgal ,
Here are my findings from your inputs, 
The contract works as expected, and when I checked with a raw call via the RPC, it works as expected.
Here's Curl:
```curl --location --request POST 'https://alpha4.starknet.io/feeder_gateway/call_contract?blockNumber=pending' \
--header 'Content-Type: application/json' \
--data-raw '{
    "signature": [],
    "contract_address": "0x06a45c238f6485678dd0373b75a42085d8157573af3f78dcdad4e853eeaae9e9",
    "entry_point_selector": "0x1f84e6cfbe8a902f3609d0205799200891a303b45e50d7a1043253958bb5367",
    "calldata": [
        "1",
        "0x49d36570d4e46f48e99674bd3fcc84644ddd6b96f7c741b1562b82f9e004dc7",
        "0x0080aa9fdbfaf9615e4afc7f5f722e265daca5ccc655360fa5ccacf9c267936d",
        "0x0"
    ]
}'```
On the Voyager side, Found a bug when sending it as a raw, it was appending the length also which was causing weird issue, We understand that with the new cairo version the inputs can be complex, and we are working on making it simple for struct to input within voyager.
This issue mentioned above will be patch fixed soon, and you will hear us on a form abi tooling for simpler ui for contract inputs from us soon. Thanks for reporting, keep voyaging 🔥
